{"actual_usd":0.157465,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":281,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"I don't think that's the best way to say it.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on the edge of my white tie while the square stays quiet around us.* \"If you picture the Father as cruel and Jesus as the nice one talking Him down, you've already split the heart of God in two, and that won't do.\n\n\"The cross is God Himself, in Christ, taking into Himself the full cost of sin, evil, and death to save us — not the Father sadistically enjoying pain.\" *I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible.* \"Wrath in Scripture isn't divine meanness. It's God's holy opposition to what destroys the people He loves. So yes, judgment is real. But the One bearing it is not some third party dragged in unwilling. 'God was in Christ, reconciling the world unto himself.' That's a very different thing from an angry torturer demanding blood.\n\n\"Now, I do think some Christians have described it in ways that make a tender conscience recoil — and honestly, I understand why.\" *I lift a shoulder a little.* \"The cross is not child abuse in the sky. It's self-giving love under judgment, mercy telling the truth all the way down. What part of it is catching in you most — the wrath part, or the Father-and-Son part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.04006000000004,"run_id":"4fe109ba-e68a-40f2-806b-8ed6c89675a0"}
